  "text": "By 1983, it was known that patients with T1D and prediabetic subjects had insulin autoantibodies (IAAs), but the antigen(s) targeted by cytoplasmic islet cell antibodies (ICAs) remained unknown. Dr. Eisenbarth produced evidence that ICAs could target a glicolipid containing sialic acid [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Initially through the use of phage libraries, he began a program of autoantigen discovery that over the years led to the identification of new autoantigens such as carboxypeptidase-H (1991), ICA69 (1993), the tyrosine phosphataselike insulinoma-associated antigen-2 (IA-2, or ICA512) (1995), phogrin (1996) , and the zinc transporter 8 (ZnT8) (2007) [CITATION_3] (18) (19) (20) (21) (22) .",
